There is no outside obligation requiring action from me. There is no opportunity to be evaluated or feel judged. It's as if the deadlines themselves were causing me to feel overwhelmed to the point of paralysis. Take away the deadlines and expectations (real and imagined) and I have been energized, inspired and motivated to finish tasks that have been screaming for attention for years. My home is finally getting the attention it needs and I can see the potential for vast improvements on day-to-day livability. My once beautiful outdoor respite has been a virtual junkyard for the last few years due to neglect. At the end of today, the garden path is cleared, Significant landscaping and structural improvements have been completed, over 350 loose bricks are being used by friends for a patio. Have you ever gathered, transported and delivered 350 bricks? I enclosed my laundry area so I have a mud room instead of an outside laundry area. Planning to finish the floor tonight. Hanging the door was a big hassle . . . AND, I have 2 pick-up truck loads of unusable trash ready to go PLUS enough unwanted clothes, toys and other items just waiting to be donated - at least 3 trips to the Salvation Army drop-off will be necessary. This is just the tip of the iceberg. All because I wasn't pressured to meet a deadline?!?

anything_else: Bring at the upper end of the 50-59 demographic, very many friends are of similar ages or greater, and so there are many friends and family members to be concerned about. So a first worrying phase of this has been contacting people and making sure they are aware of risks and keeping safe. But the other VERY worrying thing, if you are close to 60 and male (but with no known pre-existing conditions), is that while you do not come into the most vulnerable groups, there is still a risk of death, and a greater risk of a very unpleasant spell in ICU. Yet Government policy is geared towards protecting the even higher risk groups. So you wonder what the heck to do if/when lockdown is lifted - do you just go and take the risk? Now as a poker player I look at risk and percentages in a different way to most people. 1-2% risk of death is not huge, but it is still risk or ruin that you want to avoid if at all possible. 5-15% risk of hospitalisation is a very sizeable risk of something very unpleasant indeed. So from the beginning where people were saying 'oh it's like flu, it's just a 1% risk', I have been very concerned. Of course if you put it to those same people that if they get on a plane, it has a 1% chance of crashing, they would be off it pronto. Unfortunately in the UK our Government has screwed up in typical British amateur public school fashion and listened to the small group of scientists advising them (SAGE, whose membership and minutes are kept secret) who went for an influenza mitiation/herd immunity approach, where NZ and Asian countries went for a full SARS/elimination approach. So we are stuck here with a policy based on exposing 80% of the population to it over a number of waves (with maybe 40l+ deaths), to get immunity that may not be long-lasting if it really exists at all. And if you want to be in the 20% not exposed, then it could be isolation for 12 months or more.    And the Prime Minister, who failed to interrogate the advice from SAGE, and failed to convene COBRA until March (spending his time instead on Brexit and/or finishing his book on Shakespeare) has not only paid the price of it himself with illness, but left us with a rudderless government by nonentities while he recuperate at Chequers (and/orfinishes his book on Shakespeare).  When you find yourself agreeing with every word of Piers Morgan, you know you have slipped into a terrible alternate reality.

My family and friends (and myself) are very lucky that we can work from home and hence avoid most of the risks of contagion. But I can see that people are starting to get tired of the social distancing and are starting to loosen up their own rules, and that makes me worry that the risks of infection are going to stay with us for a longer time than if everybody was really careful.

My mom is high risk because asthma that was completely untreated for years due to no health insurance caused permanent lung damage, completely preventably, and she's never been the same. Her health has been in decline in other ways too and she's on immunosuppressants as well. Her boyfriend lost his job and she can't work, and they live on the brink as it is. (I didn't list him as family, sorry, he's not my family and I can't stand him, but my mom is dependent on him financially.) Because they have lived in a motel room for years instead of properly renting, I'm not sure if protections against eviction will apply to them.    I'm estranged from most of the rest of my family and don't know how they're doing. My grandma lives in Long Island and is in her 80s, I worry about her, but I feel like they're probably mad at me for arguing with her. I actually stormed out at like 3 AM on Easter Sunday, 2012, after a short-lived attempt to reconnect--we'd been estranged for 20 years before that. I'm at the point where I wonder if I should google her name to see if she died or something. Maybe this makes me sound like a bad person, I can't get along with anyone in my family except for my mom. I didn't even find out until years after the fact about my uncle being a survivor in one of the WTC buildings on 9/11, or my grandpa dying in a hit-and-run. But even when I was a child and making more of an effort, I never got invited to any weddings or funerals. I've never been to a wedding or a funeral in my life, and I'm 35. When my great-grandmother died, my mom got a postcard from her sister after the funeral was over so she couldn't come, and she'd been very close with her grandma, closer than her sister was actually. Normal people get to have families, I get to wonder idly if mine are alive or dead and maybe years later I'll get a postcard or a Facebook comment letting me know. It's not like it really changes my life or anything...it's just sad. I feel like I already lived under the floorboards of society long before this, and I'm just dully watching all the panic and pandemonium upstairs. We definitely never have all been in anything together, and it's not about to start now.

You need to have a roommate question because HOLY CRAP has my relationship with my roommates COMPLETELY BLOWN UP. There are 3 people in my house including me, there were 4. In early March one of my roommates left because she could not stand the behaviour of my my other two roommates surrounding the virus. I, and those two roommates are physically disabled in different ways. They were taking their shit out on her, and kind of on me, and then after she left, BLEW UP and THREATENED ME when I was trying to advocate for my medical needs that were in contrast to their COMFORT. They threatened me because they believe their comfort is more important than my bodily NEEDS. We are on seperate quarantines, I am taking it very seriously and have been self-quarantining for a month. My two roommates that are left could barely be considered to be sheltering in place and go out 3-4 times a week to shop when they don't actually need to. They are in their 70s with medical complications. I am in my late 30s with extreme medical complications. I guarantee you there is some serious abuse happening not just with families and domestic partners, but also, roommates. I am the main cleaner of the house yet I still have to tip toe around THEIR schedule, the guy of this two person couple is the one that threatened me, and when I am out cleaning FOR THE ENTIRE HOUSE, he will come out, disrupt, I have to leave the room and wait, he doesn't use gloves, and then when he is finally done, I have to start ALL OVER AGAIN, the power dynamics and entitlement during this situation has gone way over the top with these people and I am struggling to just keep my daily together while tip toeing around these people and just barely getting me needs met. I live in poverty which is why I have to live with roommates. You are missing a huge subsection of the population by not really acknowledging this type of living situation very well. I am stuck here because of the virus. I can not just move away to safety because of being immunocompromised. Meanwhile I have to worry about the biohazards that my two roommates are, and their complete lack of caring about how they are affecting me, in both a contamination way, and a psychological way.
